            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>&ldquo;We don&rsquo;t know if anyone is ever going to be executed in this state again,&rdquo; Woodall said. &ldquo;The way that they could get closure was to accept this plea today and this absolutely, as much as we can be guaranteed that a person will never get out of prison, this plea helps guarantee that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Executions are particularly rare in Orange County, which has not returned a death penalty sentence in approximately 70 years.</p>
<p>Jonathan Broun, an attorney who represented Atwater, said it was good that the death penalty was avoided.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This was definitely a senseless and tragic crime,&rdquo; Broun said in an interview with The Chronicle. &ldquo;We appreciate both the district attorney&rsquo;s office and the Carson family for allowing [Atwater] to have a plea that allowed him to live. Although it is a very harsh punishment, we know that they were doing it out of a love for their daughter.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Carson&rsquo;s family was present at the hearing. Raleigh lawyer Wade Smith made a statement to the public on behalf of the family.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We are not planning to address the court today about the loss of Eve,&rdquo; Smith wrote in an e-mail. &ldquo;Everyone knows it was a horrendous blow to us to lose her. And we are not going to confront the coward who selfishly took her life. Instead we will devote ourselves to the memory of Eve and to living our lives in a way that honors her.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Smith added that he expects the Carson family will attend Lovette&rsquo;s trial sessions or ask Smith to represent the family.</p>

